# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: admiralty-islands
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] The word *admiral* in Middle English comes from Anglo-French *amiral*, "commander", from Medieval Latin *admiralis*, *admirallus*.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] The 1818 edition of Samuel Johnson's *A Dictionary of the English Language*, edited and revised by the Rev.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] The quote from John Minsheu's Dictionarie in Spanish and English (1599), given in Johnson's Dictionary, has been confirmed as being accurate.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] Those Phanariots who attained the princely position of dragoman of the fleet served under the Ottoman admiral having administration of the Aegean islands and the Anatolian coast.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] Central Command, introduced Vice Admiral Mark I.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] One alternate etymology proposes that the term admiral evolved, instead, from the title of Amīr al-Umarāʾ (أمير الأمراء).
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] Under the reign of the Buyid dynasty (934 to 1062) of Iraq and Iran, the title of Amīr al-Umarāʾ, which means prince of princes, came to denote the heir-apparent, or crown prince.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] This alternate etymology states that the term was in use for the Greco-Arab naval leaders (e.g.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] Christodulus) in the Norman-Arab-Byzantine culture of Norman Sicily, which had formerly been ruled by Arabs, at least by the early 11th century.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] During this time, the Norman Roger II of Sicily (1095–1154) employed a Greek Christian, known as George of Antioch, who previously had served as a naval commander for several North African Muslim rulers.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] Roger styled George in Abbasid fashion as *Amir of Amirs*, or Amīr al-Umarāʾ, with the title becoming Latinized in the 13th century as *ammiratus ammiratorum*.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] The Sicilians and later the Genoese took the first two parts of the term from their Aragon opponents and used them as one word, *amiral*. .
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] The French gave their sea commanders similar titles while in Portuguese and Spanish the word changed to *almirante*.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] As the word was used by people speaking Latin or Latin-based languages it gained the "d" and endured a series of different endings and spellings leading to the English spelling *admyrall* in the 14th century and to *admiral* by the 16th century.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] The etymology of a word does not suggest the antiquity of the word as it may have appeared in other languages with entirely different pronunciations.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] The Greek ναύαρχος, for instance, which is pronounced "naúarkhos", existed from very ancient times in Greece.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] The word "admiral" has come to be almost exclusively associated with the highest naval rank in most of the world's navies, equivalent to the army rank of general.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] However, this was not always the case; for example, in some European countries prior to the end of World War II, admiral was the third highest naval rank after general admiral and grand admiral.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] The rank of admiral has also been subdivided into various grades, several of which are historically extinct while others remain in use in most present-day navies.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] The Royal Navy used the colours red, white, and blue, in descending order to indicate seniority of its admirals until 1864; for example, Horatio Nelson's highest rank was vice-admiral of the white.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] The generic term for these naval equivalents of army generals is flag officer.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] Some navies have also used army-type titles for them, such as the Cromwellian "general at sea".
[src:admiralty-islands/admiral] While the rank is used in most of NATO countries, it is ranked differently depending on the country.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-group] The **Admiralty Group** of islets consists of eight rocky outcrops within 2 km of the north of Lord Howe Island.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-group] Roach Island is the largest, being about 15 ha in area, 800 m long and 86 m in maximum height, with a much-photographed 15-metre-tall tunnel at its northern end.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-group] Basalt lava flows are crossed by many dikes.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-group] Vegetation consists of grasses, sedges and a few bushes.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-group] The islets are noted in spring and summer for nesting populations of seabirds in greater numbers than anywhere on Lord Howe Island.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-group] These are mainly sooty terns, masked boobies and brown noddies.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-group] Boat trips take visitors to Roach Island for a bird colony experience.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island-cuscus] The **Admiralty Island cuscus** or **Manus Island spotted cuscus** (***Spilocuscus kraemeri***) is a species of marsupial in the family Phalangeridae.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island-cuscus] It is endemic to the Admiralty Islands of Papua New Guinea.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island-cuscus] It is the smallest member of the genus *Spilocuscus*, and the female has a black back, while the male has blackish spots on a white background.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island-cuscus] Listed as Near Threatened because, although it is common within its small range (its extent of occurrence is less than 2,000 km2), there is continuing decline in both quality of habitat and numbers of individuals, thus making the species close to qualifying for Vulnerable under criterion B.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island-cuscus] The increasing human population pressures and the low fecundity of this relatively long-lived animal are cause for concern.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island-cuscus] Populations of this species should be closely monitored.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] Angoon, a traditional Tlingit community home to 572 people, is the only settlement on the island, although an unpopulated section of the city of Juneau comprises 264.68 km2 (102.19 sq mi) (6.2 percent) of the island's land area near its northern end.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] The island's total population at the 2000 census was 650.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] The national monument is sacred to the Angoon Community Association, a Tlingit tribe, who live in Angoon on the western coast of the island.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] The Tlingits fought to make protection for the island a part of ANILCA legislation, and continue to engage in stewardship of the island's natural resources.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] Many of Angoon's residents make daily subsistence use of the national monument.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] The Tlingit language name for the island is **Xootsnoowú**, which is commonly interpreted as "Fortress of the Bear(s)", and gives its name to hooch.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] The island was named by British naval officer George Vancouver in honor of his Royal Navy employers, the Admiralty.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] Joseph Whidbey, master of the *Discovery* during Vancouver's 1791–95 expedition, explored it in July–August 1794, in the process circumnavigating it.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] The Admiralty Island National Monument was created December 1, 1978, by President Jimmy Carter.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] In the Alaska National Interest Lands Conservation Act Congress designated all but 18,351 acres (74.26 km2) (74 km2) of the monument as the Kootznoowoo Wilderness, ensuring that the vast bulk of this monument is permanently protected from development.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] The monument is administered by the U.S.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] In 1986 it was named a biosphere reserve along with Glacier Bay National Park under the Man and the Biosphere Programme.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] Western hemlock, Sitka spruce and western redcedar dominate the prolific rainforest vegetation; wildlife in abundance includes brown bear, bald eagles, many species of salmon, whales, and deer.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] Admiralty Island is home to the highest density of brown bears in North America.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] An estimated 1,600 brown bears inhabit the island, outnumbering Admiralty's human residents nearly three to one.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] It has more brown bears than the entire lower 48 states, and one of the highest densities of bald eagles in the world.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] Murder Cove is located at the southernmost portion of the island and was home to the Tyee Company whaling station.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] The Greens Creek mine is an underground silver, gold, zinc and lead mine located on the northwest end of the island, within the national monument.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] Admiralty Island offers opportunities for outdoor recreation.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] The 32-mile Cross Admiralty Canoe Route is a popular destination for backcountry canoeing and kayaking, traversing the breadth of the island through a series of lakes, streams and trail portages, with several cabins and shelters along the way.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] While the modern route was laid out and constructed by the Civilian Conservation Corps in the 1930s, it follows traces long used by the island's native inhabitants for hunting, fishing and trading.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] The Pack Creek Brown Bear Viewing Area offers visitors the opportunity to observe brown bears in their natural habitat as they fish for salmon and interact with one another during the summer months.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] Permits are required for all visitors to Pack Creek; they can be obtained through the Forest Service.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] Over recent decades, various fishing and outdoor recreation lodges have opened up on the island with most of these lodges operating in the Tlingit town of Angoon.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] There’s also one lodge on a small, privately held plot of land within the national monument.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-island] The Point Retreat Light is located on the northern tip of Admiralty and was an important aid-to-navigation.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The **Admiralty Islands campaign** (Operation Brewer) was a series of battles in the New Guinea campaign of World War II in which the United States Army's 1st Cavalry Division took the Japanese-held Admiralty Islands.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Acting on reports from airmen that there were no signs of enemy activity and the islands might have been evacuated, General Douglas MacArthur accelerated his timetable for capturing the Admiralties and ordered an immediate reconnaissance in force.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The campaign began on 29 February 1944 when a force landed on Los Negros, the third-largest island in the group.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] By using a small, isolated beach where the Japanese had not anticipated an assault, the force achieved tactical surprise, but the islands proved to be far from unoccupied.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] A furious battle over the islands ensued.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] In the end, air superiority and command of the sea allowed the Allies to heavily reinforce their position on Los Negros.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The 1st Cavalry Division could then overrun the islands.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The campaign officially ended on 18 May 1944.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The Allied victory completed the isolation of the major Japanese base at Rabaul that was the ultimate objective of the Allied campaigns of 1942 and 1943.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] A major air and naval base was developed in the Admiralty Islands that became an important launching point for the campaigns of 1944 in the Pacific.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] This campaign marked the end of MacArthur's Operation Cartwheel, which was a multi-theater operation conducted to turn the powerful Japanese base of Rabaul into a de facto prisoner-of-war camp.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The Admiralty Islands lie 200 miles (320 km) north east of the mainland of New Guinea and 360 miles (580 km) west of Rabaul, only two degrees south of the equator.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The climate is tropical, with constant high temperatures and high humidity and an annual rainfall of 154 inches (3,900 mm).
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] December to May is the north west monsoon season, with prevailing winds from that direction.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The largest island in the group is Manus Island, which is about 49 miles (79 km) across from east to west and 16 miles (26 km) wide from north to south.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The interior is mountainous, with peaks rising to 3,000 feet (910 m) and largely covered with thick tropical rainforest.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The largely uncharted coastline had numerous reefs.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The shoreline consisted mostly of mangrove swamp.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The third largest island in the province, Los Negros lies to the northeast of Manus, from which it is separated by the narrow Loniu Passage.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The island contains two important harbours of its own, Papitalai on the west coast, which connects with Seeadler Harbour, and Hyane on the east coast.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The two are separated by a 50-yard (46 m) wide sandy spit.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Here, the natives built a skidway over which they could drag canoes between the two harbours.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Los Negros curves horseshoe-like, forming a natural breakwater for Seeadler Harbour, the remainder of which is enclosed by Manus and a series of smaller islands.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The main entrance was through a 1.5-mile (2.4 km) wide passage between Hauwei and Ndrilo Islands.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Seeadler Harbour is about 20 miles (32 km) across from east to west and 6 miles (9.7 km) wide from north to south, and up to 120 feet (37 m) deep.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] In July 1942, the Joint Chiefs of Staff approved a series of operations against the Japanese bastion at Rabaul, which blocked any Allied advance along the northern coast of New Guinea towards the Philippines or northward towards the main Japanese naval base at Truk.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] In keeping with the overall Allied grand strategy of Europe first, the immediate aim of these operations was not the defeat of Japan but merely the reduction of the threat posed by Japanese aircraft and warships based at Rabaul to air and sea communications between the United States and Australia.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] By agreement among the Allied nations, in March 1942 the Pacific theatre was divided into the South West Pacific Area, under General Douglas MacArthur, and the Pacific Ocean Areas, under Admiral Chester W.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Rabaul fell within MacArthur's area but the initial operations in the southern Solomon Islands came under Nimitz.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The Japanese reaction was more violent than anticipated and some months passed before the Guadalcanal Campaign was brought to a successful conclusion.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Meanwhile, General MacArthur's forces—primarily Australian—fought off a series of Japanese offensives in Papua in the Kokoda Track Campaign, Battle of Milne Bay, Battle of Buna-Gona, and the Battle of Wau.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] At the Pacific Military Conference in March 1943, the Joint Chiefs of Staff approved the latest version of General MacArthur's Elkton plan for an advance on Rabaul.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Owing to a shortage of resources, particularly heavy bomber aircraft, the final stage of the plan, the capture of Rabaul itself, was postponed until 1944.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] By July 1943, the Joint Chiefs were considering the possibility of neutralising and bypassing Rabaul, but the navy would still need a forward fleet base.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The Admiralty Islands, already a part of the Elkton plan, could serve this purpose, as they contained flat areas for airstrips, space for military installations, and Seeadler Harbour, which was large enough to accommodate a naval task force.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] On 6 August 1943, the Joint Chiefs of Staff adopted a plan that called for the neutralisation rather than the capture of Rabaul, and scheduled the invasion of the Admiralty Islands for 1 June 1944.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Throughout January 1944, AirSols aircraft based in the Solomon Islands and Royal Australian Air Force (RAAF) aircraft based on Kiriwina kept up a sustained air offensive against Rabaul.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Under steady and relentless pressure, the Japanese air defence began to weaken, allowing a landing to be made on 15 February by New Zealand troops on the Green Islands, which lie little more than 100 miles (160 km) from Rabaul.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] On 16 and 17 February, the US Pacific Fleet's Task Force 58 attacked the main Japanese base at Truk.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Most Japanese aircraft were recalled to defend Truk and 19 February saw the last significant interception of Allied aircraft over Rabaul.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Meanwhile, on 13 February General MacArthur, who received an intelligence windfall from the capture of Japanese Army code books by his Australian soldiers at Sio, had issued orders for the invasion of the Admiralty Islands, codenamed Operation Brewer, which was now scheduled for 1 April.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Forces assigned included the 1st Cavalry Division; No.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] 73 Wing RAAF, providing close air support; the 592nd Engineer Boat and Shore Regiment (EBSR); the US Marines' 1st Amphibious Tractor Battalion; and US Naval Construction Battalions ("Seabees") to build the naval base—a total of 45,000 personnel.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] However, on 23 February 1944 three Fifth Air Force B-25 Mitchell bombers flew low over Los Negros.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The airmen reported that there were no signs of enemy activity and the islands had been evacuated.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Lieutenant General George Kenney, the commander of Allied Air Forces in the South West Pacific Area, went to MacArthur and proposed that the unoccupied islands be quickly taken by a small force.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Orders went out on 24 February 1944 for a reinforced squadron of the 1st Cavalry Division to carry out a reconnaissance in force in just five days time.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] If the Admiralty Islands were indeed evacuated, they would be occupied and a base developed.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] If the enemy was unexpectedly strong, then the force could be withdrawn.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] General MacArthur and Vice Admiral Thomas C.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Kinkaid, the commander of Allied Naval Forces in the South West Pacific Area, would be on hand to make the decision but otherwise they delegated command to Rear Admiral William Fechteler, the commander of Amphibious Group 8 of Rear Admiral Daniel E.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] To accommodate them, the light cruiser USS *Phoenix* was ordered to sea.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] At the time, she was in Brisbane, with over 300 of her crew on shore leave.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Trucks with bull horns broadcast the code word recalling the crew.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] To achieve surprise, and to reach the Admiralty Islands in just five days, high speed transports (APDs) were required; Landing Ships, Tank (LSTs) were too slow to make the required distance in the time.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Only three APDs were available: USS *Brooks*, *Humphreys* and *Sands*.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The remaining troops were carried on nine destroyers: USS *Bush*, *Drayton*, *Flusser*, *Mahan*, *Reid*, *Smith*, *Stevenson*, *Stockton* and *Welles*.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Between them, the destroyers and APDs carried 1,026 troops.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] This force was commanded by Brigadier General William C.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Chase, commander of the 1st Brigade, 1st Cavalry Division.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] When an aide expressed concern over assigning such a hazardous mission to a unit without combat experience, General MacArthur recalled how the 5th Cavalry had fought alongside his father's troops in the campaign against Geronimo.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Willoughby's G-2 (intelligence) section did not agree with the airmen's assessment the islands were unoccupied.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Drawing on Ultra and Allied Intelligence Bureau reports from interrogating local civilians, it reported on 15 February that there were 3,000 Japanese troops in the Admiralty Islands.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] On 24 February, it revised the estimate to 4,000.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] G-2 attributed the lack of anti-aircraft fire to the Japanese logistical situation, believing it was a measure to conserve ammunition.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Lieutenant General Walter Krueger, the commander of US Sixth Army later recalled no one at his headquarters believed the islands unoccupied.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] In the original plan, a team of Alamo Scouts was to have thoroughly reconnoitred the island before the landing.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Krueger had a six-man party of Alamo Scouts inserted on the southern coast of Los Negros by PBY under cover of a bombing raid on 27 February.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The scouts reported the south coast was "lousy with Japs".
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The Japanese defence of the Admiralties fell under the Eighth Area Army, based at Rabaul and commanded by General Hitoshi Imamura.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] In September 1943, as a result of the failure to stop Allied advances in New Guinea and the Solomons, the Imperial General Headquarters (IGHQ) had decided to constrict Japan's defensive perimeter in the south and central Pacific to a new line stretching from the Banda Sea to the Caroline Islands.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The IGHQ charged Imamura with holding his portion of the new line, which included the Admiralties, as long as possible to allow the Japanese navy and army time to prepare "decisive" counterattacks against Allied forces.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Maintaining control of the Admiralties was crucial to the Japanese defensive plans, as possession of the islands by the Allies would place the key Japanese stronghold at Truk within range of heavy bombers.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Apparently not expecting the Allies to move on the Admiralties so quickly, IGHQ gave Imamura until the middle of 1944 to complete the defensive preparations for his command.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] At this time the largest Japanese unit in the islands was the 51st Transport Regiment, which had arrived on Los Negros in April.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Imamura sought reinforcements for the Admiralties in late 1943 and early 1944.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] In October 1943 he requested an infantry division for the islands, but none was available.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] A subsequent proposal to transfer the 66th Regiment from the Palaus, where it was being rebuilt after suffering heavy losses, to the Admiralties was also unsuccessful as IGHQ believed that the Eighteenth Army had greater need for this unit.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The Imperial Japanese Navy (IJN) also rejected Imamura's suggestion that a special naval landing force unit be dispatched to the islands.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Following this disaster Imamura directed the 38th Division to dispatch a battalion to the islands, and 750 men of the 2nd Battalion, 1st Independent Mixed Regiment arrived there on the night of 24/25 January.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] A subsequent attempt to ship an infantry and an artillery battalion to the Admiralties was frustrated by Allied air and submarine attacks, but 530 soldiers of the 38th Division's 1st Battalion, 229th Infantry Regiment arrived there on the night of 2 February.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Most of these troop movements were detected by Allied intelligence.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Allied G-2 had identified the presence of all these units in the Admiralties, though their designation was not known in all instances.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] While the 1st Battalion, 229th Infantry Regiment was a veteran of several campaigns, it was short of equipment and lacked its battalion artillery guns.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The 2nd Battalion, 1st Independent Mixed Regiment was led by reserve officers who had seen action in China, but most of its enlisted men were recalled reservists who had not previously been in battle.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The 51st Transport Regiment had constructed an airstrip on Lorengau and commenced another, known as Momote Airstrip, at the Momote Plantation on Los Negros.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Lorengau was used as a staging point for aircraft moving between Rabaul and airstrips in North East New Guinea.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The importance of the Admiralty Islands to the Japanese increased as the result of Allied advances in New Guinea and New Britain which blocked off other air routes.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] By February, both airstrips were unserviceable and the antiaircraft guns were silent to conserve ammunition and conceal their positions.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Ezaki had ordered his men to neither move nor fire in daylight.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The chosen landing site was a small beach on the south shore of Hyane Harbour near the Momote airstrip.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The airstrip could be seized quickly; but the surrounding area was mangrove swamp, and the harbour entrance was only about 750 yards (700 m) wide.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] "Since the whole operation was a gamble anyway," Samuel Eliot Morison noted, "one might as well be consistent." The gamble paid off.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The Japanese had not anticipated a landing at this point and the bulk of their forces were concentrated to defend the beaches of Seeadler Harbour, on the other side of the island.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The weather on 29 February 1944 was overcast with a low cloud ceiling that prevented most of the planned air strike.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Only three B-24s and nine B-25s found the target.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The naval bombardment was therefore extended for another 15 minutes.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Each APD lowered four LCPRs (Landing Craft, Personnel, Ramped).
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Each LCPR carried its maximum load of 37 men, who boarded by climbing over the APDs' sides and down cargo nets.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The unarmoured LCPRs were still used because davits had not been strengthened to carry the heavier, armoured LCVP (Landing Craft, Vehicle, Personnel).
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The first wave landed without casualties at 08:17, but once the bombardment lifted the Japanese emerged from their dugouts and machine guns and shore batteries began firing.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The landing craft, on returning, came under crossfire from enemy machine guns on both sides of the harbour.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The fire became so heavy the second wave was forced to reverse course until the enemy fire was suppressed by destroyers.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The third and fourth waves also came under fire.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Four of the twelve LCPRs had been damaged.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Three were soon repaired, but they could not be risked further, for without them, the reconnaissance force could not be evacuated.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The emergency plan provided for an APD to enter the harbour and take troops off from a jetty but this would clearly be a desperate measure indeed.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Over the next four hours, the boats continued to make trips to the beach, but only when it was believed destroyers had suppressed enemy fire.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Heavy rain made it safer by reducing visibility.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The last destroyer was unloaded at 12:50.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] By this time, the navy had lost two men dead and three wounded.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Sporadic opposition allowed them to set up the antiaircraft machine guns on the beach, unload supplies, and patrol inland.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Two soldiers were killed and three wounded.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] At 16:00, General MacArthur and Admiral Kinkaid came ashore.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] A lieutenant warned him a Japanese sniper had been killed in the vicinity just a few minutes before.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] "That's the best thing to do with them," the General replied.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] He decided to stay, ordering Chase to hold his position until the follow-up force arrived, then returned to *Phoenix*.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Fechteler's force departed at 17:29, the transports having unloaded and most of the bombardment force having exhausted its ammunition.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] *Bush* and *Stockton* remained to provide on-call naval fire support.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Chase pulled his troops back into a tight perimeter.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] There was no barbed wire, so the whole area had to be covered.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The ground was hard coral, which was good for airbase construction but made it difficult to dig foxholes.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The twelve .50 calibre (12.7mm) machine guns were positioned in the front line.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] There was fighting throughout the night as small groups of Japanese attempted to infiltrate the position.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] A break in the weather allowed three B-25s of the 38th US Bomb Group to drop supplies at 08:30.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Four B-17s of the 375th Troop Carrier Group each dropped three tons of supplies, including blood plasma, ammunition, hand grenades, and barbed wire.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Some of the ammunition fell beyond the perimeter but for some reason men who moved out to retrieve it were not fired upon.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The Japanese were not expected to make another effort until dark but at around 16:00 a Japanese patrol was discovered that had somehow managed to infiltrate the perimeter in broad daylight and penetrate to within 35 yd (32 m) of Chase's command post.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] A sniper fired on the command post, and fire was directed at the patrol.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Major Julio Chiaramonte, S-2 (intelligence officer) of the task force, set out with four men to silence the sniper.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] As his party closed in, there were a series of explosions.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Three Japanese had committed suicide with hand grenades, while another had committed *seppuku* with his sword.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Fifteen dead officers and sergeants were counted, including Captain Baba, the commander of the Japanese battalion which made the attack the preceding night.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The Japanese launched another attack on the perimeter at 17:00 but could make little progress in the face of American firepower.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The next morning saw the arrival of the follow-up force, six LSTs, each towing an LCM, escorted by the destroyers USS *Mullany* and *Ammen* and HMAS *Warramunga* and destroyer minesweepers USS *Hamilton* and *Long*.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The LSTs entered Hyane Harbour and beached, coming under mortar fire as they did so.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] *LST-202*, crewed by the United States Coast Guard, replied with 3 in (76 mm) and Bofors 40 mm guns.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The LSTs were unloaded over the next seven hours.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] In the process, ammunition, construction equipment, and stores piled up.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] To accommodate a proper dispersal of stores, Chase ordered an attack to expand the perimeter.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] B-25s of the 345th US Bomb Group were intercepted by an estimated fifteen Japanese fighters.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] These were driven off by eight escorting P-47 Thunderbolt fighters, which claimed eight Japanese aircraft shot down.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Two B-17s of the 69th US Troop Carrier Squadron on a supply dropping run were also attacked, and claimed to have shot one of their attackers down.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Two of the four B-25 squadrons dropped bombs in areas occupied by American troops, two of whom were killed and four wounded before the 12th US Air Liaison Party could correct the error.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Both squadrons of the 5th Cavalry attacked at 15:00.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] All objectives were taken and a new, larger defensive perimeter was prepared.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The 40th Naval Construction Battalion had landed expecting to work on Momote airstrip.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Instead, they were ordered to use their equipment to clear fields of fire and construct fortifications, and were given a section of the perimeter to defend.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Six trenches were dug out by a bulldozer and ten men stationed in each.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Their ditch digger scooped out a 300-yard (270 m) trench which formed a secondary line of defence.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The airstrip's revetments were transformed into heavy machine gun posts.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The two destroyer minesweepers were supposed to sweep the entrance to Seeadler Harbour between Hauwei and Ndrilo Islands but fire from at least one Japanese 4-inch (102 mm) gun on Hauwei Island prevented them from entering the harbour.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Captain Emile Dechaineux, commanding the destroyers supporting the forces ashore, brought *Ammen*, *Bush*, *Mullany* and *Warramunga* around and bombarded the island.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The Japanese guns ceased fire but came alive again when another attempt was made to sweep the channel.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Dechaineux then called off the effort, ordering the DMSs to join him.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The destroyers bombarded Japanese guns covering the entrance to Hyane Harbour to allow the LSTs to leave unmolested.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] One LST left with between 20 and 30 truckloads of stores still aboard.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The LSTs did not wish to remain after dark as a Japanese attack was expected.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Dechaineux escorted them part of the way until he received an order from Admiral Barbey for *Ammen*, *Mullany*, *Warramunga*, and *Welles* to remain off Los Negros.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] *Ammen* and *Mullany* bombarded Hauwei Island again in the morning, setting off a couple of ammunition dumps, but still came under accurate fire from four or five guns, and Dechaineux was forced to inform Barbey that he was unable to overcome the island's guns.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Krueger was gravely concerned about the seriousness of the situation on Los Negros.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] In response to urgent request from Chase, Krueger arranged with Barbey for the movement of the rest of the 1st Cavalry Division to be expedited.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] At Krueger's request, the 2nd Squadron, 7th Cavalry would travel in the three APDs.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Other units would arrive on 6 and 9 March instead of 9 and 16 March.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Krueger realised that Hyane harbour was too small to support the entire division, but there were good beaches around Salami Plantation on the western shore of Los Negros.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] To use them, and to permit a shore-to-shore operation against Manus from Los Negros, Seeadler Harbour would have to be opened up.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] From the Japanese perspective, the battle was not going too well either.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The Japanese had expected a landing on Seeadler Harbour, this being the logical American objective, and had concentrated their forces around the Lorengau airfield.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The defence of the Momote airstrip and Hyane harbour was the responsibility of Baba Force, built around Captain Baba's 1st Battalion, 229th Infantry Regiment.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Colonel Ezaki ordered Baba to attack the beachhead but a suspicion the Hyane Harbour landing was a diversion, coupled with false reports of enemy activity at Salami had him retain the 2nd (Iwakami) Battalion of the 1st Independent Infantry Regiment there instead of sending it to assist Baba Force.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] By 2 March, Ezaki had resolved to attack the Hyane beachhead with his whole force.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The difficulties imposed by the terrain, and disruption by American artillery and Allied naval gunfire, forced a postponement of the attack to the night of 3 March.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] At 21:00, a lone Japanese plane dropped eight bombs, cutting telephone wires.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Once it had departed, yellow flares went up and a Japanese infantry attack was launched, supported by mortar fire.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Offshore, Dechaineux' destroyers came under attack from four *Betty* bombers.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] 1st Squadron, 5th Cavalry, was attacked by about two reinforced platoons, which were met by heavy automatic weapons and mortar fire.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The heavy jungle in this sector permitted some infiltration but the Japanese force was not strong enough to overrun the position.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The main Japanese attack was delivered by 2nd Battalion, 1st Independent Mixed Regiment, from the direction of the native skidway, together with detachments from the Porlaka area, and fell on 2nd Squadron, 5th Cavalry.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The troopers noticed a change in Japanese tactics.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Instead of infiltrating silently, they advanced across the open, talking and in some cases singing.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Their advance took them straight into anti-personnel mines and booby traps, which duly exploded, and then into the fields of fire of the Americans' automatic weapons, including several .30 water-cooled Browning machineguns, but the advance continued.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The guns of the 211th Coast Artillery (AA) Battalion and 99th Field Artillery Battalion fired through the night, attempting to break up the Japanese attack from Porlaka.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Shortly after midnight, Japanese barges attempted to cross Hyane harbour but were engaged by anti-aircraft guns and did not reach the American positions.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] A Bofors 40 mm gun position was captured by the Japanese, who in turn were driven off by the Seabees.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Manning the .30s, the 5th Cavalry's gunners piled up the Japanese dead until the guns had to be moved to get clear fields of fire.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] One of the Browning guns that held the position was later left in its place, as a monument.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Sergeant Troy McGill occupied a revetment with his squad of eight men.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] All were killed or wounded except McGill and another man, whom he ordered to fall back to the next revetment.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] McGill fired his rifle until it jammed, then clubbed the Japanese with it until he was killed.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] He was posthumously awarded the Medal of Honor.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] By dawn, the Japanese attack had subsided.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Over 750 Japanese dead were counted in and around the American positions.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] American casualties were 61 dead, and 244 wounded, including nine dead and 38 wounded Seabees.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The 2nd Squadron, 5th Cavalry and the 40th Naval Construction Battalion received Presidential Unit Citations.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] General Chase called for an airdrop of ammunition, prodigious quantities of which had been expended during the night, and had *Warramunga* fire on the native skidway.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The morning of 4 March saw the arrival of the 2nd Squadron, 7th Cavalry, which relieved the 2nd Squadron, 5th Cavalry.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Swift, the commander of the 1st Cavalry Division, arrived aboard *Bush* and assumed command.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] He ordered the 2nd Squadron, 7th Cavalry to attack across the native skidway.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The 2nd Squadron, 5th Cavalry therefore went back into the line to relieve them.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] While the relief was taking place, the Japanese launched a daylight attack.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] This was repulsed by the cavalrymen, with the help of artillery and mortar fire, but the American attack was delayed until late afternoon.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] It then ran into a Japanese minefield and by dawn the advance had only reached as far as the skidway.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The 12th Cavalry was ordered to follow the 2nd Squadron, 7th Cavalry in its advance to the north, and to capture the Salami Plantation.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The road to Salami was little more than a muddy track in which vehicles soon became bogged.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The Japanese also obstructed the route with ditches, felled trees, snipers, and booby traps.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Booker of ANGAU used his local knowledge to guide the 12th Cavalry and the three tanks to Salami.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Here the Japanese put up a fierce fight that lasted over an hour.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The tanks fired canister shot shells into buildings and high-explosive shells into the slits of Japanese bunkers.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The inhabitants of the area informed the ANGAU detachment the Japanese had retreated across Seeadler Harbour to Papitalai Mission.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] This, therefore, became the next objective.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The 5th Cavalry would attack Papitalai Plantation from the east while the 2nd Squadron, 12th Cavalry would attack Papitalai Mission.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The 5th Cavalry captured Porlaka without opposition and crossed Lemondrol Creek in canvas and rubber boats.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Cornelius fought an estimated 50 Japanese, who ultimately withdrew.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Cornelius, who was credited with killing four, was severely wounded and died the next day.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] He was posthumously awarded the Distinguished Service Cross.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Because of the coral reef, conventional landing craft could not be used for the landing at Papitalai Mission.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The five LVTs, one a combat type and the other four cargo-carrying, set out from Hyane Harbour to Salami Plantation but the road was so bad that only the combat and one cargo LVT were available in time.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The attack went ahead anyway, preceded by an airstrike and artillery bombardment by the 271st Field Artillery Battalion.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The combat LVT fired 24 M8 4.5-inch rockets.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Return fire was received from Japanese mortars and machine guns, and a 75 mm howitzer.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The first wave had to hold alone in the face of fire from Japanese bunkers for 45 minutes until the LVTs returned with the next wave.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Later, they fought off a counterattack by about 30 Japanese.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Joined by a third LVT which had eventually managed to make it to Salami, the LVTs made 16 trips across the harbour before nightfall curtailed operations, transporting part of the 2nd Squadron, 12th Cavalry, along with rations, water and ammunition, and evacuating the dead and wounded.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Colonel Ezaki reported the American attack on Papitalai Mission to the Eighth Area Army in Rabaul, promising a night counterattack on the position; but no attack was delivered.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The Japanese withdrew, and no further messages were ever received from Ezaki.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The task of silencing the Japanese guns guarding Seeadler Harbour fell to Rear Admiral Victor Crutchley's Task Force 74 (TF74), consisting of the heavy cruiser HMAS *Shropshire*, light cruisers USS *Phoenix* and *Nashville*, and destroyers USS *Bache*, *Beale*, *Daly*, and *Hutchins*.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] They bombarded Hauwei Island for an hour on 4 March but on 6 March USS *Nicholson* was struck by a Japanese shell fired from Hauwei.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] With minesweepers scheduled to attempt to enter Seeadler Harbour again on 8 March, Admiral Kinkaid ordered Crutchley to try again.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] On the afternoon of 7 March, TF74 bombarded Hauwei, Ndrilo, Koruniat, Pityilu and northern Los Negros.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] *Shropshire* fired 64 8-inch (203 mm) and 92 4-inch (102 mm) shells, while the American cruisers and destroyers expended 1,144 5-inch (127 mm) and 6-inch (152 mm) shells.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The next day, two destroyers, two minesweepers, an LCM (flak) and six LCMs carrying trucks and supplies entered the Seeadler Harbour without being fired upon.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] This cleared the way for the 2nd Brigade, 1st Cavalry Division to land at Salmi on 9 March.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] By 7 March, the Seabees had the Momote airfield ready.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Artillery spotting aircraft began operating from the strip on 6 March and a B-25 made an emergency landing the next day.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Guided by a B-25, twelve P-40 Kittyhawks of No.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] 76 Squadron RAAF arrived from Kiriwina via Finschhafen on 9 March, the remaining twelve aircraft of the squadron following the next day.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] They were joined by the ground crew of No.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] 77 Squadron RAAF, which had arrived by LST on 6 March.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] 73 Wing RAAF arrived over the next two weeks, including the Kittyhawks of No.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] 77 Squadron RAAF and Supermarine Spitfires of No.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Operations began on 10 March and henceforth ships and ground units in the Admiralties had air support just minutes away.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The ANGAU Detachment reached the town of Mokerang on 9 March and found fifty inhabitants.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The Detachment was relieved to find islanders had not been deliberately ill-treated by the Japanese.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The retreating Japanese had stripped their gardens of food, leaving the civilian population hungry, so ANGAU arranged for them to be provisioned by the Americans.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Operations on Los Negros had now reached the mopping-up stage, but an estimated 2,700 Japanese troops remained on Manus.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] General Swift decided to land Brigadier General Verne D.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Mudge's 2nd Brigade at Lugos Mission, west of Lorengau.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Lorengau, known to be heavily fortified, was an important objective.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] It had an airfield, and four roads converged there.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] As a preliminary, the 302nd Cavalry Reconnaissance Troop was ordered to locate sites from which the artillery could cover landings on Manus.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Three patrols were sent out by LCVP on 11 March.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The first found Bear Point on Manus free of Japanese but lacking sites for artillery emplacements.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The second scouted the Butjo Luo Islands.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] They found the islands apparently unoccupied, with good sites on the northern island.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The third patrol, 25 officers and men of the 302nd Cavalry Reconnaissance Troop, two officers from the 99th Field Artillery Battalion, with WO2 A.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Robinson of ANGAU and Kaihu, a native of Mokerang, as guides, set out for Hauwei in an LCVP, escorted by PT 329, one of the PT boats now operating from the tender USS *Oyster Bay* in Seeadler Harbour.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] As the patrol moved ashore, Major Carter S.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Vaden spotted a well camouflaged bunker and threw two hand grenades into it.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] When they exploded, concealed Japanese mortars and machine guns commenced firing on the patrol and the craft offshore.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The PT was hit, her commander wounded, and she withdrew.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The LCVP headed toward the shore where she picked up five men, including Robinson and Kaihu.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The LCVP retracted and headed out to sea but then sighted another group on the beach.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] She headed back in to pick them up, despite her commander being wounded, and succeeded.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] As she backed off the beach again, she was holed by a mortar round and began taking on water.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Meanwhile, the damaged PT had reported what had happened and a bomber was sent to investigate.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Flying low, it spotted the men in the water, and another PT boat was sent to the rescue, covered by the destroyer HMAS *Arunta*.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] After three hours in the water, the LCVP's survivors were picked up by the PT boat.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Eight Americans, including Vaden, had been killed and fifteen wounded, including the entire LCVP crew.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Kaihu was missing and Robinson was contemplating how he would break the news to his family when Kaihu walked in, having swum back to Los Negros.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Swift postponed the landing on Lugos and ordered the 2nd Squadron, 7th Cavalry to capture Hauwei.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Once again, Robinson acted as guide, notwithstanding severe sunburn from his time in the water the previous day.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The landing was covered by the destroyers *Arunta*, *Bush*, *Stockton* and *Thorn*; a pair of rocket-firing LCVPs and the LCM (flak), which fired 168 4.5-inch (114 mm) rockets; the guns of the 61st Field Artillery Battalion on Los Negros; and six Kittyhawks of No.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] 76 Squadron dropped 500-pound (230 kg) bombs.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The assault was made from three cargo-carrying LVTs.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] To save wear and tear, they were towed across Seeadler Harbour by LCMs and cut loose for the final run in to shore.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The cavalrymen found well constructed and sited bunkers with interlocking fields of fire covering all approaches, and deadly accurate snipers.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The next morning an LCM brought over a medium tank, for which the Japanese had no answer, and the cavalrymen were able to overcome the defenders at a cost of eight killed and 46 wounded; 43 dead Japanese naval personnel were counted.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The 61st and 271st Field Artillery Battalions moved to Hauwei, while the 99th established itself on Butjo Luto.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The attack on Manus got underway on 15 March.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Before dawn, two troops of the 8th Cavalry, six cargo carrying LVTs and the combat LVT were loaded on board an LST for the 18 kilometres (11 mi) trip across Seeadler Harbour from Salami.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Beaches at Lugos, about 4 kilometres (2.5 mi) west of Lorengau were chosen in preference to those nearer Lorengau, which were known to be heavily defended.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The Japanese had evidently not expected a landing at Lugos and their positions there were quickly overrun.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The 1st Squadron, 8th Cavalry then advanced eastward until it was stopped by a Japanese bunker complex on the edge of the Lorengau airstrip.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] An artillery barrage was brought down, followed by an airstrike by P-40 Kittyhawks with 500 pound bombs.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The cavalry resumed its advance, and occupied a ridge overlooking the airstrip without opposition.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] In the meantime, the 7th Cavalry had been landed at Lugos from the LST on its second trip and took over the defence of the area, freeing the 2nd Squadron, 8th Cavalry to join the attack on Lorengau.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The first attempt to capture the airstrip was checked by an enemy bunker complex.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] A second attempt on 17 March, reinforced by the 1st Squadron, 7th Cavalry and tanks, made good progress.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The advance then resumed, with Lorengau itself falling on 18 March.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Although there had been plenty of fighting, the main Japanese force on Manus had not been located.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Advancing inland towards Rossum, the 7th Cavalry found it on 20 March.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Six days of fighting around Rossum were required before the 7th and 8th Cavalry reduced the entrenched Japanese positions there.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The Japanese bunkers, actually log and earth pillboxes, proved resistant to artillery fire.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] As the Japanese on Los Negros ran out of food and ammunition, the fight became increasingly unequal.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] A last stand by fifty Japanese in the Papitalai Hills on 24 March marked the end of organised Japanese resistance on Los Negros.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The end of organised resistance on Los Negros and Manus still left a number of islands in Japanese hands.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] To minimise civilian casualties, ANGAU quietly evacuated these islands in advance of the American operations.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Pityilu was believed occupied by about 60 Japanese.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] On 30 March the 1st Squadron, 7th Cavalry was transported there from Lorengau by 10 LCMs towing seven LVTs.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] With the lessons of Hauwei in mind, the landing was covered by bombardment by destroyers, artillery, and two Landing Craft Support, plus an air strike by Kittyhawks and Spitfires.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The landing was unopposed, but a strong Japanese position was encountered which was overcome with the aid of artillery and tanks.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Some 59 Japanese were killed compared with eight Americans killed and six wounded.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The same treatment was given to Ndrilo and Koruniat on 1 April but the 1st Squadron, 12th Cavalry found them unoccupied.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] This was notable for being the only amphibious operation of the war carried out by the United States in dugout canoes.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The final landing was on Rambutyo on 3 April by the 2nd Squadron, 12th Cavalry.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] This time, six LCMs and six LCVPs were used instead of the LVTs.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] As a result, the first waves grounded on a reef and troopers had to wade ashore through the surf.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Fortunately for them, there was no opposition.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] The Japanese, hiding in the interior, were eventually located by ANGAU and 30 Japanese were killed and five captured.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Patrols continued hunting for Japanese throughout the islands.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] Increasingly, the cavalry followed up sightings reported by the natives.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] On Los Negros, the 302nd Cavalry Reconnaissance Troop killed 48 and captured 15 Japanese during May.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] On Manus, some 586 Japanese dead were counted and 47 prisoners taken.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p01] General Krueger officially declared the campaign over on 18 May.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] Discussions concerning the scope and nature of base development in the Admiralty Islands were held in early February between representatives of SWPA and Admiral William Halsey, Jr.'s neighbouring South Pacific Area (SOPAC).
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] The original intention was forces from SWPA would capture the islands and construct the airbase, while SOPAC would be responsible for the development of the naval base.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] The SOPAC representatives indicated they would not be able to supply troops or materials in the early stages, so it was resolved SWPA would also undertake the initial stages of naval base development.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] Admiral Nimitz recommended to the Joint Chiefs of Staff that development and control of the base facilities be placed under SOPAC by extending its border westward to include the Admiralties.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] MacArthur was furious; the borders of SWPA could not be changed without the consent of the Australian government.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] Nimitz's proposal was eventually turned down by the Joint Chiefs but not before MacArthur restricted access to the facilities to ships of the United States Seventh Fleet and British Pacific Fleet.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] Halsey was summoned to MacArthur's headquarters in Brisbane on 3 March 1944, and the two agreed to a compromise.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] Responsibility for the development of the base passed from Krueger's Alamo Force to Kinkaid's Allied Naval Forces on 18 May 1944.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] It was proposed control would ultimately pass to SOPAC but it never did.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] Momote airfield was found to have been constructed on a coral subbase with an overburden of coconut palm humus, over which the Japanese had laid a thin layer of coral and coral sand.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] This would not withstand heavy use, so 40th Naval Construction Battalion, 8th Engineer Squadron, and Shore Battalion of the 592nd EBSR had to strip away the humus and lay a new coral surface.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] Just 3,600 feet (1,100 m) of runway was sufficient for the Kittyhawks and Spitfires but the runway was increased to 7,800 feet (2,400 m) by late April.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] B-24s of 5th Bombardment Group moved in on 18 April 1944 and flew their first mission, against Woleai two days later.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] Plans called for a second airfield at Salami Plantation, but surveys revealed that the site was unsuitable and a new site was found in a coconut plantation near Mokerang.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] While the 46th Naval Construction Battalion cleared an access road, the 836th Engineer Aviation Battalion constructed the runway, and the 104th and 46th Naval Construction Battalions built the taxiways and dispersal areas.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] As at Momote, the humus had to be removed to reach the coral subgrade, which was then graded and compacted.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] In places the coral was so hard explosives had to be used.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] The work required the clearing of 1,100 acres (4.5 km2) and the removal of 18,000 coconut trees.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] B-24s of 307th Bombardment Group (the "Long Rangers") arrived on 21 April 1944.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] They participated in raids on Biak and supported the Battle of Biak in May.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] A fighter base to provide repair and overhaul facilities for carrier aircraft was constructed by the 78th Naval Construction Battalion on Ponam Island.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] As half of the work area was swamp, coral was blasted and dredged from the ocean bed and used as landfill.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] Another facility for carrier aircraft was built on Pityilu by the 71st Naval Construction Battalion in May and June 1944, along with accommodation for 2,500 men.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] The eastern end of Pityilu was cleared and a fleet recreation centre was built that could accommodate up to 10,000 at a time.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] Construction of the naval base on Los Negros was the responsibility of the 2nd Naval Construction Regiment, with the 11th, 58th and 71st Naval Construction Battalions.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] At Lombrum Point, the Seabees built three installations: a seaplane repair base, a ship repair base, and a landing craft repair base.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] A 250-long-ton (250 t) pontoon drydock was provided for servicing the landing craft.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] Development of facilities on Manus was taken in hand by the 5th Naval Construction Regiment, with the 35th, 44th and 57th Naval Construction Battalions, which arrived in mid-April, and the 140th Naval Construction Battalion, which was attached in June.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] They erected 128 storage buildings and 50 refrigerators, each of 680 cubic feet (19 m3) capacity.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] A water supply system was developed to supply 4,000,000 US gallons (15,000,000 L) per day.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] Two systems were developed, one using streams in the Lombrum area that supplied 2,700,000 US gallons (10,000,000 L) per day, and another for outlying areas that used wells to produce 850,000 US gallons (3,200,000 L) per day.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] The system included water treatment plants, reservoirs, and pipes.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] All construction work was completed by April 1945, with the base remaining in use until the end of the war.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] In his final report on the campaign, General Krueger reported 3,280 Japanese dead had been counted and 75 had been captured.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] Perhaps 1,100 more were missing, and were never seen again.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] American casualties were 326 killed, 1,189 wounded, and four missing.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] Some 1,625 Americans had been evacuated for all causes, including wounds and illness.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] ANGAU reported one native had been killed and one wounded in action, three were killed by the Japanese, and 20 accidentally killed and 34 wounded by air, artillery, and naval bombardment.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] The value of the Admiralty Islands to the Allies was enormous.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] Their capture saved more lives than they cost by obviating the need to capture Truk, Kavieng, Rabaul, and Hansa Bay and thereby speeding up the Allied advance by several months.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] As an airbase, the Admiralties' value was great, for aircraft based there ranged over Truk, Wewak, and beyond.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] As a naval base, their value was greater still, as they combined a fleet anchorage with major facilities.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] A well-known rule of thumb is that an attacking force needs a 3:1 superiority to ensure success.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] In the opening stages of the battle of Los Negros, the ratio was more like 1:4.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] In the end the Allies won, "simply because," wrote Morison, "the United States and Australia dominated that stretch of ocean and the air over it." When queried about the naval support, General Chase replied, "they didn't support us; they saved our necks".
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] Chase's own defensive tactics were also a vital factor.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] He was awarded the Bronze Star for his part, as was MacArthur.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] Allied commanders, and later historians, debated whether the Admiralty Islands Campaign was the bold action of a great commander or a reckless endeavour that courted disaster.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] Admiral Fechteler felt, "we're damn lucky we didn't get run off the island," and Admiral Barbey, for one, believed the original plan would have resulted in over-running the islands in short order with fewer casualties.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] It would certainly have been much less risky, but it is doubtful whether an assault on the well-defended beaches of Seeadler Harbour would have resulted in fewer casualties.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] Whereas, in accelerating both MacArthur and Nimitz's campaigns, it shortened the war by at least a month.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] Thus, in the final analysis, the campaign "had the great virtue of hastening victory while reducing the number of dead and wounded".
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] For the Japanese, the loss of the Admiralties meant the loss of their outpost line in the South Eastern Area.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] Imperial Headquarters now ordered the preparation of a new line in Western New Guinea.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] The Admiralties operation also indicated the Allies were becoming more ambitious and might bypass Hansa Bay.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-campaign-p02] Accordingly, the Eighteenth Army in New Guinea was ordered to prepare to defend Aitape and Wewak as well.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-languages] The **Admiralty Islands languages** are a group of some thirty Oceanic languages spoken on the Admiralty Islands.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-languages] They may include Yapese, which has proven difficult to classify.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands-languages] As noted, Yapese and Nguluwan may be part of the Admiralty Islands languages as well.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] The **Admiralty Islands** are an archipelago group of 40 islands in the Bismarck Archipelago, to the north of New Guinea in the South Pacific Ocean.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] These are also sometimes known as the **Manus Islands**, after the largest island of the chain.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] These rainforest-covered islands constitute Manus Province, the smallest and least-populous province of Papua New Guinea, in its Islands Region.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] The province had a population of 60,485 at the 2011 Census.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] Many of the smaller Admiralty Islands are atolls and uninhabited.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] The larger islands in the center of the group are Manus Island and Los Negros Island.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] The other larger islands are Tong Island, Pak Island, Rambutyo Island and Lou Island to the east, Mbuke Island to the south and Bipi Island to the west of Manus Island.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] Baluan Island, to the south of Manus Island, is the main island of the Pam Islands, where the Baluan-Pam language is spoken.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] Other islands that have been noted as significant places in the history of Manus include Ndrova Island, Pityilu Island and Ponam Island.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] The temperature of the Admiralty Islands varies little throughout the year, reaching daily highs of 30–32 °C (86–90 °F) and 20–24 °C (68–75 °F) at night.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] Average annual rainfall is 3,382 mm (133 in) and is somewhat seasonal, with June–August being the wettest months.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] Manus reaches an elevation of 700 m (2,300 ft) and is volcanic in origin and probably broke through the ocean's surface in the late Miocene, 8–10 million years ago.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] The substrate of the island is either directly volcanic or from uplifted coral limestone.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] The main town in the islands is Lorengau on Manus, connected by road to an airport on nearby Los Negros Island, otherwise transport around the islands is by boat.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] There is little tourism, although the seas are attractive to divers, including Jean-Michel Cousteau who spent time on nearby Wuvulu Island in the 1970s.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] Due to the isolated location, the rain forests of the Admiralty Islands are home to rare and endemic species of birds, bats and other animals, and are considered a separate ecoregion, the **Admiralty Islands lowland rain forests**.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] The majority of the forests on Manus still remain, but some of the smaller islands have been cleared for coconut farming.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] The typical tree species are various *Calophyllum* and *Sararanga* species.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] The 58.5 km2 (22.6 sq mi) Ndrolowa Wildlife Management Area was created in March 1985 south of Lorengau on Manus Island and contains both terrestrial and marine regions.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] A further 240 km2 (93 sq mi) protected area has been established around the highest mountain on Manus, Mount Dremsel, but the level of protection remains undetermined in the UNEP World Database on Protected Areas.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] Three of the bird species endemic to Admiralty Islands have been listed as vulnerable in the IUCN Red List: Manus fantail (*Rhipidura semirubra*), superb pitta (*Pitta superba*) and Manus masked owl (*Tyto manusi*), and the Manus dwarf kingfisher (*Ceyx dispar*) listed as near threatened.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] Three other birds are endemic to Admiralty Islands but are classified as non-threatened or least concern: white-naped friarbird (*Philemon albitorques*), Manus monarch (*Monarcha infelix*) and Manus hawk owl (*Ninox meeki*).
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] The islands are home to two endemic *Cornufer* frogs (*Cornufer admiraltiensis* and *Cornufer latro*) and four lizards, while the emerald green snail of Manus was the first terrestrial snail to be listed as vulnerable by the IUCN.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] Along with New Guinea, the Bismarck Archipelago and the Solomon Islands Archipelago, the Admiralty Islands were first inhabited approximately 40,000 years ago, in the initial wave of migration out of Southeast Asia that also populated Australia.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] This early society appears to have cultivated taro, and to have deliberately introduced wild animals from New Guinea such as bandicoots and large rats.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] Obsidian was gathered and traded throughout the Admiralty Islands archipelago.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] The Lapita culture arose around 3,500 years ago, and its extent ranged from the Admiralty Islands to Tonga and Samoa.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] Its origins are contested, but it may well have been a product of another wave of migration from Southeast Asia.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] Lapita society featured renowned pottery, stilt houses, the introduction of domestic animals such as pigs, dogs, and chickens, and substantial developments in agriculture and boat technology, allowing long-distance trade to develop.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] Lapita society, as a distinct culture and extended trade network, collapsed around 2,000 years ago.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] The first European to visit the islands was the Spanish navigator Álvaro de Saavedra when trying to return from Tidore to New Spain in the summer of 1528.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] Saavedra charted Manus as *Urays la Grande*.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] Its visit was also reported in 1616 by the Dutch navigator Willem Schouten.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] The name 'Admiralty Islands' was devised by Captain Philip Carteret of the British Royal Navy in 1767.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] Between 1884 and 1914 the area was administered as a German colony.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] In November 1914, the islands were occupied by troops of the Australian Naval and Military Expeditionary Force landed from the SS *Siar*.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] A few shots fired from a machine gun on *Siar* over the heads of the tiny German garrison at Lorengau were the last shots fired in the battle.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] After the war, the islands were governed by the Commonwealth of Australia under a League of Nations mandate.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] Japanese troops landed on Manus Island on 7 April 1942.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] In 1944, Japanese forces occupying the islands were attacked and defeated by Allied forces in Operation Brewer.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] Subsequently, a large American airbase and Manus Naval Base was built at Lombrum near Lorengau.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] Following Papuan independence in 1975, the Admiralty Islands became part of Papua New Guinea.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-islands] They became the Manus Province of the Islands Region in Papua New Guinea.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The **Admiralty** was a department of the Kingdom of Great Britain and from 1801 of the Government of the United Kingdom that was responsible for the command of the Royal Navy.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] Historically, its titular head was the Lord High Admiral – one of the Great Officers of State.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] For much of its history, from the early 18th century until its abolition, the role of the Lord High Admiral was almost invariably put "in commission" and exercised by the Lords Commissioner of the Admiralty, who sat on the governing Board of Admiralty, rather than by a single person.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Admiralty was replaced by the Admiralty Board in 1964, as part of the reforms that created the Ministry of Defence and its Navy Department (later Navy Command).
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Admiralty was among the most important departments of the British Government, because of the Royal Navy's role in the expansion and maintenance of the English overseas possessions in the 17th century, the British Empire in the 18th century, and subsequently.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The modern Admiralty Board, to which the functions of the Admiralty were transferred in 1964, is a committee of the tri-service Defence Council of the United Kingdom.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] This Admiralty Board meets only twice a year, and the day-to-day running of the Royal Navy is controlled by a Navy Board (not to be confused with the historic Navy Board).
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] It is common for the various authorities now in charge of the Royal Navy to be referred to as simply 'The Admiralty'.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] Since 1964, the title of Lord High Admiral of the United Kingdom has been vested in the monarch; the title was awarded to Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh by Queen Elizabeth II on his 90th birthday in 2011 and remained with him until his death in 2021.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] There also continues to be a Vice-Admiral of the United Kingdom and a Rear-Admiral of the United Kingdom, both of which are honorary offices.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The office of Admiral of England (later Lord Admiral, and later Lord High Admiral) was created around 1400; there had previously been Admirals of the northern and western seas.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] King Henry VIII established the Council of the Marine—later to become the Navy Board—in 1546, to oversee administrative affairs of the naval service.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] Operational control of the Royal Navy remained the responsibility of the Lord High Admiral, who was one of the nine Great Officers of State.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] This management approach would continue in force in the Royal Navy until 1832.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] King Charles I put the office of Lord High Admiral into commission in 1628, and control of the Royal Navy passed to a committee in the form of the Board of Admiralty.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The office of Lord High Admiral passed a number of times in and out of commission until 1709, after which the office was almost permanently in commission (the last Lord High Admiral being the future King William IV in the early 19th century).
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] These principal officers came to be known as the Navy Board responsible for 'civil administration' of the navy, from 1546 to 1832.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] This structure of administering the navy lasted for 285 years, however, the supply system was often inefficient and corrupt its deficiencies were due as much to its limitations of the times they operated in.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The various functions within the Admiralty were not coordinated effectively and lacked inter-dependency with each other, with the result that in 1832, Sir James Graham abolished the Navy Board and merged its functions within those of the Board of Admiralty.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] At the time this had distinct advantages; however, it failed to retain the principle of distinctions between the Admiralty and supply, and a lot of bureaucracy followed with the merger.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] In 1860 saw big growth in the development of technical crafts, the expansion of more admiralty branches that really began with age of steam that would have an enormous influence on the navy and naval thought.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] Between 1860 and 1908, there was no real study of strategy and of staff work conducted within the naval service; it was practically ignored.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] All the Navy's talent flowed to the great technical universities.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] This school of thought for the next 50 years was exclusively technically based.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The first serious attempt to introduce a sole management body to administer the naval service manifested itself in the creation of the Admiralty Navy War Council in 1909.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] Following this, a new advisory body called the Admiralty War Staff was then instituted in 1912, headed by the Chief of the War Staff who was responsible for administering three new sub-divisions responsible for operations, intelligence and mobilisation.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The new War Staff had hardly found its feet and it continually struggled with the opposition to its existence by senior officers they were categorically opposed to a staff.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The deficiencies of the system within this government department could be seen in the conduct of the Dardanelles campaign.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] There were no mechanisms in place to answer the big strategic questions.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] Sir John Jellicoe came to the Admiralty in 1916.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] He reorganised the war staff as following: Chief of War Staff, Operations, Intelligence, Signal Section, Mobilisation, Trade.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] It was not until 1917 that the admiralty department was again properly reorganised and began to function as a professional military staff.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] In May 1917, the term "Admiralty War Staff" was renamed and that department and its functional role were superseded by a new "Admiralty Naval Staff"; in addition, the newly created office of Chief of the Naval Staff was merged in the office of the First Sea Lord.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] Also appointed was a new post, that of Deputy Chief of the Naval Staff, and an Assistant Chief of the Naval Staff; all were given seats on the Board of Admiralty.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] This for the first time gave the naval staff direct representation on the board; the presence of three senior naval senior members on the board ensured the necessary authority to carry through any operation of war.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Deputy Chief of Naval Staff would direct all operations and movements of the fleet, while the Assistant Chief of Naval Staff would be responsible for mercantile movements and anti-submarine operations.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The office of Controller would be re-established to deal with all questions relating to supply; on 6 September 1917, a Deputy First Sea Lord, was added to the Board who would administer operations abroad and deal with questions of foreign policy.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] In October 1917, the development of the staff was carried one step further by the creation of two sub-committees of the Board—the Operations Committee and the Maintenance Committee.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The First Lord of the Admiralty was chairman of both committees, and the Operations Committee consisted of the First Sea Lord and Chief of Naval Staff, the Deputy First Sea Lord, Assistant Chief of Naval Staff, and Fifth Sea Lord.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] Full operational control of the Royal Navy was finally handed over to the Chief of Naval Staff (CNS) by an order in Council, effective October 1917, under which he became responsible for the issuing of orders affecting all war operations directly to the fleet.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] It also empowered the CNS to issue orders in their own name, as opposed to them previously being issued by the Permanent Secretary of the Admiralty in the name of the Board.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] In 1964, the Admiralty—along with the War Office and the Air Ministry—were abolished as separate departments of state, and placed under one single new Ministry of Defence.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] Within the expanded Ministry of Defence are the new Admiralty Board which has a separate Navy Board responsible for the day-to-day running of the Royal Navy, the Army Board and the Air Force Board, each headed by the Secretary of State for Defence.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] In order to deliver this the Naval Staff was organised into specialist Divisions and Sections.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] When the Admiralty unified with the Ministry of Defence in 1964 they were re designated as Directorates of the Naval Staff.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Admiralty Departments, which provides the men, ships, aircraft and supplies to carry out the approved policy.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The departments are superintended by the various offices of the Sea Lords.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Department of the Permanent Secretary which was the general co-ordinating agency, regulating naval finance, providing advice on policy, conducing all correspondence on behalf of the Board and maintaining admiralty records.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] Its primary component to deliver this is the Admiralty Secretariat, sections of the Secretariat (other than those which provide Common Services) were known as Branches.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Board of Admiralty consisted of a number of Lords Commissioners of the Admiralty.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Lords Commissioners were always a mixture of admirals, known as Naval Lords or Sea Lords and Civil Lords, normally politicians.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The quorum of the Board was two commissioners and a secretary.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The president of the Board was known as the First Lord of the Admiralty, who was a member of the Cabinet.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] After 1806, the First Lord of the Admiralty was always a civilian, while the professional head of the navy came to be (and is still today) known as the First Sea Lord.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Lords Commissioners of the Admiralty were the members of The Board of Admiralty, which exercised the office of Lord High Admiral when it was not vested in a single person.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The commissioners were a mixture of politicians without naval experience and professional naval officers, the proportion of naval officers generally increasing over time.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The First Sea Lord and Chief of Naval Staff was the Chief Naval Adviser on the Board of Admiralty to the First Lord and superintended the offices of the sea lords and the admiralty naval staff.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Navy Board was an independent board from 1546 until 1628 when it became subordinate to, yet autonomous of the Board of Admiralty until 1832.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] Its principal commissioners of the Navy advised the board in relation to civil administration of the naval affairs.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Navy Board was based at the Navy Office.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] Office of the Additional Civil Lord of the Admiralty.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] Office of the Parliamentary and Financial Secretary to the Admiralty.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] It evolved from *Admiralty Navy War Council, (1909–1912) which in turn became the Admiralty War Staff, (1912–1917) before finally becoming the Admiralty Naval Staff in 1917.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] It was the former senior command, operational planning, policy and strategy department within the British Admiralty.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] Office of the Vice Chief of the Naval Staff.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] Offices of the Assistant Chiefs of the Naval Staff.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] The Secretary's Department consisted of members of the civil service it was directed and controlled by a senior civil servant Permanent Secretary to the Board of Admiralty he was not a Lord Commissioner of the Admiralty, he functioned as a member of the board, and attended all of its meetings.
[src:admiralty-islands/admiralty-united-kingdom] In some cases, the term *admiralty* is used in a wider sense, as meaning *sea power* or *rule over the seas*, rather than in strict reference to the institution exercising such power.
